(window.webpackJsonp=window.webpackJsonp||[]).push([[8],{266:function(e,t,o){"use strict";o.r(t);var n=o(1),i=(o(0),o(260));t.default=function(){return Object(n.b)(i.d,null,Object(n.b)(i.g,{title:"Class Times"}),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"title"},"The Ving Tsun System"),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"Ving Tsun is a dense little system that focuses on efficient use of body mechanics and energy while promoting what we view as the five essential attributes: Balance, Timing, Coordination, Relaxation and Sensitivity."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},'The system breaks down into 3 hand forms two weapon and the famous "Wooden Man" form.'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},'Each piece of the system lays the foundation for the next. You cannot separate or dissect it. Thinking "oh the wooden dummy looks cool" or "those swords look fierce." and learning only that piece without the context the system provides will leave you only "wearing the model\'s clothes."'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"We don't promote memorization of techniques and principles. We use repetition to re-tune your reflexes. The system is simple and easily digestible. It is laid out methodically with each step laying the foundation for the next."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"Here is how the system breaks down (high level view)"),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"title"},"Hand forms"),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"subtitle"},"Siu Lim Tao"),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"The first of the three hand forms, Siu Lim Tao is dense and fascinating."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"Essentially it's broken down into three parts. It initially assumes you know nothing and patiently explains the basic vocabulary of the system."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"The first section is centered on using your body to show you correct positions and structure. The second how to generate power in various directions and lastly putting them together properly."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"The lessons are given to you methodically; first you learn proper stance, how to “draw your centerline”, how to punch, make a fist and so on."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"As you progress through the system you will come to see this form in many different lights."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"subtitle"},'Chum Kiu "Searching the Bridge"'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"One cannot understand the nature of Chum Kiu without first learning the basics offered in Siu Lim Tao."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"Once you have learn those basics from a stationary position it is time to apply them while moving and interacting with another person."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},'The focus here is on finding the "connection point" or bridge between you and your target, to do so offensively while maintaining defensive advantages.'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"subtitle"},'Biu Jee "Shooting Fingers"'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"In my experience this is the most misunderstood form in the system. Some believe it contains movements so dangerous that to use them would instantly kill your opponent and their whole family ;)."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"This is not how we view this form. Once again understanding a form in Ving Tsun you must take the others into account."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"In Siu Lim Tao you have learn proper position, structure, how to throw power and technique. Then you learn in Chum Kiu how to do this while moving and dealing with another person. What’s left? We should be done right? Not quite."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},'The question now becomes, what happens when things go wrong? When you lose position, misstep or have your “structure” compromised. Essentially Biu Jee covers the "Emergency Techniques” used to recapture what we would call optimal position. This form concludes the three hand forms.'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"title"},"Weapon Forms"),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"subtitle"},'Luk Dim Poon Kwan "6 1/2 Point Pole'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"quote"},"“Luk Dim Poon Kwan, like other elements of Ving Tsun, needs to be studied completely and for its own sake, not as a means to some other end.”",Object(n.b)("br",null),"– Grandmaster Moy Yat"),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"The 6 1/2 Point Pole refers to the number of techniques in the form. This form is used to train power, horse, centreline and provide a deeper view of the systems principles."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"subtitle"},'Pah Chum Dao "8 Slicing Knives"'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"The Bah Cham Dao are two short broad-bladed swords. Generally not part of the official curriculum, this form was traditionally withheld from students at the Sifu's discretion."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"The repetitions in this form are counted at 4 instead of the customary 3. This reminds us that the movements in the Bah Chum Dao deal death with every movement. The number 4 in Chinese Culture is synonymous with death."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},'Bah Cham Dao is used these days to train punching power, "fierceness" and footwork.'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},'Formal teaching of this form is not officially part of the system. When you are "ready" you will be taught.'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"title"},'Mok Yan Jong "Wooden Man Form"'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},'The famous Ving Tsun "Wooden Dummy" Form.'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"Historically this form has been expanded and contracted by various masters. The version we play is the one handed down by Yip Man (seen here to the left) it contains 108 movements in 8 sections."),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},'The main purpose of this form is to train your "Yee" or intent/will while maintaining appropriate positioning and structure. It is not a substitute for a live partner rather a training tool to focus on detailed aspects of the system.'),Object(n.b)(i.h,{type:"body"},"Without the foundation provided by the hand forms and the principles they contain, one cannot understand the nature of the Wooden Dummy."))}}}]);
